WEBVTT

00:02.545 --> 00:09.912
It's to be sort of the heartbeat of our discipline 
in terms of terminology, the theory base, where

00:02.545 --> 00:09.912
we've been. It's changed some with new 
postmodernism and those kinds of issues, but it's

00:09.972 --> 00:15.157
still basically the course. I started teaching 
that, and I taught program evaluation, which is

00:15.217 --> 00:24.126
now turned into the AEIS accountability system 
for the state of Texas. We go online for that. And I

00:25.647 --> 00:27.168
brought the futures class here. We had a planning 
course, but not a futures class, so I initiated the

00:31.267 --> 00:35.533
first futurism class on this campus in 1975. In 
other words, the future of public, of education.

00:39.379 --> 00:47.190
Well, it's called Planning Futurism, and it's in 
the College of Education, but I'm offering it this

00:39.379 --> 00:47.190
semester, and there's 20 students. We just closed 
it. And they're from business, engineering,

00:48.512 --> 00:52.037
agriculture. So it's an interdisciplinary 
class. And Letha Malloy was in one of my early

00:55.282 --> 00:58.607
classes, John Calhoun, we had on the committee, 
and we did one of the first futures dissertation,

00:58.840 --> 01:13.383
the first future dissertation on this campus, 
where we interviewed the great higher education

00:58.840 --> 01:13.383
stars who came in here for national conferences. 
And she did a study on Delphi, where the

01:13.904 --> 01:18.031
universities were going in the next 25 years. And 
she wound up, as you know, being a vice president at

01:18.592 --> 01:22.658
Southwest Texas State University. But John 
Calhoun was on that committee. And I'll never

01:25.773 --> 01:33.202
forget, the graduate dean at the time saw that 
proposal and said, what is this futurism stuff?

01:33.222 --> 01:34.743
What are these scenarios? And what are these 
cross-impact matrices things? And we broke the

01:37.647 --> 01:40.310
new paradigm. We created a new paradigm for new 
kinds of studies because the graduate dean at the

01:40.330 --> 01:46.116
time wasn't sure. And of course, having Calhoun on 
the committee didn't hurt.

01:51.912 --> 01:53.574
So these were all graduate courses. All graduate 
courses. A normal teaching assignment then was

01:54.615 --> 01:56.797
how many? It was two courses a semester. And you 
wind up in a hurry with a great number of doctoral

01:59.500 --> 02:05.967
students who have an interest that you have. And at 
that time, the program wasn't as large as it is now,

02:06.128 --> 02:11.734
but it was quite healthy. And I've always, since 
I've been here within the first two years, have

02:11.814 --> 02:21.244
either had somewhere between 15 and 30 students 
I'm chairing on doctoral committees. Did, back to

02:21.815 --> 02:28.683
advice, did anybody give you any do's and don'ts 
advice?

02:31.686 --> 02:32.667
You know, not really. Not really. It was just do 
your thing. And Dr. Hensling, I guess, was the only

02:36.451 --> 02:45.702
one that may have said when I would ask him things. 
But I can't remember anybody saying, this is what

02:45.742 --> 02:51.248
you do, this is what you don't do. They assumed you 
knew that since I'd been a department head and been

02:51.650 --> 02:55.636
teaching at other universities. But no, I'd say 
that was a problem. Were there any differences

02:59.182 --> 03:07.715
that you quickly noticed between TCU, Miami, 
Tulsa, and A&M? I think the inflexibility that I

03:08.115 --> 03:11.200
found here. There we had department chairs. There 
was some rotation took place. There was more

03:16.912 --> 03:30.250
liberal thinking about interdisciplinary kinds 
of issues, even though at one time we'd had an

03:16.912 --> 03:30.250
interdisciplinary education doctorate, but now 
since it had become a department, it was pretty

03:16.912 --> 03:30.250
much a turf kind of thing. It was more isolated than 
I'd seen at Miami University. I'd been on the

03:34.376 --> 03:39.443
faculty senates at Miami, and I was on the first 
faculty senate at Texas A&M. Two of us were elected

03:41.506 --> 03:45.872
from the College of Education in 1983. And I was 
fortunate enough to be one of the first elected.

03:49.640 --> 03:55.710
That was exciting, with John McDermott and all the 
group trying to say, what's the core knowledge

03:49.640 --> 03:55.710
going to be in our university? How are we going to 
deal with such things as accrediting problems

03:56.531 --> 04:05.986
when you're forcing students to take too much 
liberal arts and humanities? How are we going to

04:06.988 --> 04:12.737
become more decentralized and have more power by 
faculty? rigid department structures that this

04:13.021 --> 04:17.226
university has become accustomed to. We were able 
to shatter and break a lot of that, and we were

04:17.266 --> 04:25.395
really concerned about the kind of hold that the 
department has had on the faculty. And that was a

04:26.056 --> 04:30.060
meaningful three years to be on that first faculty 
senate. Who were the key leaders that helped

04:30.081 --> 04:33.685
produce that faculty senate? John McDermott got a 
group of people together over his department, and

04:33.945 --> 04:42.775
he was very instrumental in getting the group 
together. Paul Parish was involved in that. I was

04:47.205 --> 04:48.047
involved in it. David Erlandson here was involved 
in it. I'm trying to think of some of the others. Old

04:54.899 --> 04:59.466
Bill Barzak was very much involved and helpful. 
I'm trying to think of a lady who's now deceased

04:59.967 --> 05:08.442
that was in biochemistry.

05:10.143 --> 05:11.524
